kubectl:-

Command line tool to interact with k8s cluster which talks with api server 

kubectl get nodes = shows running nodes status 
kubectl get pod =shows running pod status 
kubectl create deployment NAME --image=image      #Blueprint for creating pods # most basic configuration for deployment
kubectl get replicaset = managing replicas of pod 
kubectl logs podname = To check logs 
kubectl describe pod podname = check state of pods 
kubectl exec -it podname --/bin/bash = to enter into pod 
kubectl delete deployment podname   = to delete pod 
kubectl apply -f filename.yaml 
-----------------------------------------------------
1️⃣ apiVersion
Example:
apiVersion: apps/v1

Meaning:

Tells Kubernetes which API version to use.
apps/v1 is required for Deployments in modern Kubernetes.


2️⃣ kind
Example:
kind: Deployment

Meaning:

Defines the type of object.
Deployment = manages Pods for you.


3️⃣ metadata
Example:
metadata:
  name: nginx-deployment
  labels:
    app: web

Meaning:

Basic object info.
name: name of the Deployment.
labels: optional tags used for selection, grouping, etc.


4️⃣ spec (Deployment spec)
Controls how the Deployment behaves.
Example:
spec:
  replicas: 2
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      app: nginx
  template:
    ...

Breakdown:
✔ replicas
replicas: 2

How many Pods Deployment should keep running.
✔ selector
selector:
  matchLabels:
    app: nginx

Deployment identifies Pods using these labels.
Must match template → metadata → labels.
✔ template
The Pod blueprint (super important).

5️⃣ template (Pod blueprint)
Example:
template:
  metadata:
    labels:
      app: nginx
  spec:
    containers:
    - name: nginx
      image: nginx:1.16
      ports:
      - containerPort: 8080

Breakdown:

A) template → metadata
metadata:
  labels:
    app: nginx

Meaning:

Labels applied to Pods created by the Deployment
Must match Deployment selector


B) template → spec (Pod specification)
This defines what runs inside each Pod.

6️⃣ Pod spec → containers
Example:
containers:
- name: nginx
  image: nginx:1.16
  ports:
  - containerPort: 8080

Breakdown:
✔ containers
A list because a Pod can have multiple containers.
✔ name
Name of the container inside the Pod.
✔ image
Docker image to run.
Example:
image: nginx:1.16

✔ ports
Ports exposed inside the container.
Example:
containerPort: 8080

Useful for:

Services
Probes
Networking






